text_answer.content:
The AI is misinterpreting this poem a little. There are three characters described:
Lines 1 through 3 and 5 are about an unnamed nobleman (4 is the narrator)
Line 6 introduces the nobleman's son.
Lines 7 though 18 are about this son.
19 and 20 are about Modestus.
21 through 25 is back to the son.
26 and 27 are the response to the son's joke.
28 through 31 are Modestus.
32 through 35 are the son.
36 to the end are Modestus.
With the above, comprehension 2 suggests Modestus starts off a diffident when that's a description of the son. Comprehension 3 could be right, though the nobleman isn't really a character so much as backstory (this applies to short answer 5 as well). The line described in short answer 2 refers to the son, not Modestus.

text_answer.content:
I think you know what I'm going to say about question 2...

For question 3, stanza 4 is technically using simile, but it's about the least straightforward simile I've ever seen. Unlike most versions, where 'it was as fast as a cheetah' is the standard structure, this one not only inverts it but doesn't outright say what's being compared. 'Come as the winds come, when/Forests are rendered' roughly translates to '[You] come with a ferocity that's as strong as a wind that renders forests.' I'm not totally sure if an 11th grader will get this without some level of explanation. This answer will eventually just be given away by the writing prompt.
My prediction was much more straightforward: repetition. The word come is stated six times and faster is used four times to built the momentum of the stanza (though then it'd overlap with short answer 3).

Short answer 1 gives away question 1. To a lesser extent, short answer 2 is as well.
Short answer 4 interprets a ordering of the call when most of the poem is just clarifying that all members of the Clan Conuil is expected to arrive. The answer given is correct, I guess, but I doubt a student will understand that that's when we're asking of them.

text_answer.content:
The book mentioned in the poem isn't a literal book with pages that tells a story. It's the ship that the narrator is sailing on, its passage through the water telling the story of their voyage much like an actual novel would. This is a metaphor the AI got right with question 3, so I'm not sure what's going on with question 1 (or short answers 1, 5, 6 and the writing prompt).

text_answer.content:
This passage is aggressively anti-technology. To a point that is not realistic. While I get an appreciate the sentiment, such rigidity is eventually going to get swept away by progress no matter how hard they fight. For example, eventually Mr. Torres is going to pass away and Sonia is going to implement at least some of her ideas. There's also a reason when Texas' desire to not be connected to the rest of the nation's electrical grid has lead them to have massive blackouts for a number of years now.
Even the sample essay for the writing prompt tries to argue that this is a reasonable thing. Phrases like 'isn't dependent on outside systems' are just silly. They're a rural community. Rural communities survive on their ability to produce and sell their crops. Selling their crops requires them to not be dependent on outside systems. Furthermore, they are subject to state and federal oversight (such as taxes) that suggest why Nathan's neighbors sold their farms.
The spirit of the essay is somewhat reasonable. The practicality of it is not.

text_answer.content:
Too short. Also, the final moral is wrong. Ms. Ward didn't evolve. She was forced to change to survive and hasn't proven she's grown in her ability to judge job candidates. She's only hiring Maria because Maria has proven herself capable. That's not a bad thing, especially for an executive position, but it doesn't prove Ms. Ward can recognize potential. This, I think , means the answer to question 1 is ultimately incorrect. It's what the passage wants the theme to be, but that's not what the theme is.
I would say it's more about recognizing that, with changing values, options that didn't fit can prove to be exactly what's needed - or whatever the succinct version of that is.
This also influences short answer 1 as there's no indication her perspective on diversity has meaningfully changed.

Question 2's answer is the only one with multiple items. It also overlaps with short answer 4.
Question 3 only needs to say personification.
